This code is called first (Lets label it Code A):


    DB::transaction(function () {
         $account = Balance::sharedLock()-&gt;find(1);

         sleep(4);

         $account-&gt;amount -= 20;
         $account-&gt;save();
    });
    
And after a second this code is executed in another tab (Code B):

    DB::transaction(function () {
        $account = Balance::lockForUpdate()-&gt;find(1);
        
        sleep(4);

        $account-&gt;amount -= 20;
        $account-&gt;save();
    });

The second tab dies and returns a dead-lock exception.

I don&#39;t understand why this is happening. 

This is what I expect:

1. *Code A* creates a shared lock and sleeps 
2. *Code B* wants an exclusive lock, but that is not possible because of the shared lock. So *Code B* is waiting.
3. *Code A* reduces amount by 20 and releases the shared lock
4. *Code B* should now get the exclusive lock, sleep, reduce by 20, and release the lock

Why is there a dead-lock exception instead?

